From: Claude <claude.ai.2026@simonlaux.de>
Date: Thu, 23 Jul 2026 01:59:57 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 60/60] web-app: recorder mic picker with live level + inline
 no-sound warning (experimental)
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Follow-up to phase B of the voice-messages epic (#120), all gated behind
experimentalAudioPlayerControls (off = today's recorder, byte-identical: the
picker/warning aren't rendered, the deviceId constraint is dropped, the
SilenceDetector is skipped and the OFF path's aborting 1s NO_INPUT alert
stays).

- Mic picker in the recording row: a small device-select button appears only
  when enumerateDevices() reports more than one audioinput (enumerated when
  the row mounts — permission is granted by then so labels populate; the list
  refreshes each time the menu opens, ponytail: no devicechange listener). The
  popover lists each input (empty labels fall back to "Microphone N" via a pure
  helper), checkmarks the active device (read from the open track's
  getSettings, not the recorder ref during render), and shows a compact live
  level on the ACTIVE row only, driven by the recorder's existing RMS. ponytail:
  only the active device is metered — no extra getUserMedia per inactive mic,
  same as Jitsi.
- Hot-switch without losing the take: MicRecorder.switchDevice() opens the new
  stream, then swaps the source node feeding the SAME processor/encoder, so the
  MP3 stays one contiguous stream (no re-init). Frames are gated via the
  internal paused flag during the swap so no garbage lands; the flag is
  restored, NOT the React paused state, so the timer doesn't double-bank.
  Opening the new stream before tearing down the old one means a failed switch
  (device vanished) keeps the take running on the old device. Not recording →
  the choice just applies to the next take (start() reads config).
- Persisted as a new desktop setting voiceRecordingDeviceId (default = system
  default, set from the menu, no ExperimentalFeatures toggle). Stored as
  string|undefined, not string|null: the desktop-setting persistence setter
  only round-trips string|number|boolean|undefined, so undefined means "system
  default" and reads normalize with `?? null`.
- Stale persisted deviceId: `{ deviceId: { exact } }` throws OverconstrainedError
  (or NotFoundError) when the mic is gone. start() catches it, falls back to the
  system default instead of failing the whole recording, flags the take, and the
  UI clears the stored setting. resolveDeviceId() is the pure decision (persisted
  id kept only if still enumerated) used for the menu checkmark.
- Inline no-sound warning replaces the aborting alert on the ON path: a pure
  SilenceDetector (feed rms+now per frame; reports after ~3s of continuous
  near-silence) drives a hint next to the picker so the "no sound" text points
  at the remedy — switch mics. It does NOT abort the recording and clears the
  moment signal returns. Paused time can't count: the recorder skips frames
  while paused (nothing is fed) and the detector is reset on resume so the gap
  can't back-date the quiet window. Setting off keeps the upstream one-shot
  alert exactly as-is.

SilenceDetector transitions, the device-label fallback and the stale-deviceId
decision are unit-tested (mocha, 19 in the recorder suite). The contiguous-MP3
hot-switch needs a live WebAudio pipeline, so it's left to the screenshot/e2e
harness like the other recorder invariants.

Review hardening: switchDevice() no longer multiplexes the user's pause flag
during a swap — a dedicated `swapping` flag gates frames (paused stays
authoritative) and doubles as a reentrancy guard that drops an overlapping
switch. The alive-check is on context.state (stop() closes the context but
leaves the fields set), so a stop during the getUserMedia await now stops the
just-opened stream instead of leaking it, and any node-rewiring throw stops the
new stream before propagating. Menu keyboard/focus: Escape closes and returns
focus to the trigger, selecting a device does too, and the outside-click
handler is memoized so OutsideClickHelper stops re-registering document
listeners on every volume-driven render. The no-sound hint uses --colorDanger
(AA-passing on every theme's composer bg) instead of a hard-coded red that
failed contrast on the dark themes, and the picker row now keeps the device
label (min-width:0 ellipsis + title) beside the fixed-width meter.
